---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../../components/Footer.astro';
import Comments from '../../../components/Comments.astro';
---

<Layout title="Headings - Markdown Tutorial" description="Learn how to create headings in Markdown." lang="en">
  <Header />

  <main>
    <section class="section section-dark">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="max-w-3xl">
          <p class="text-sm font-medium tracking-wider uppercase text-[var(--color-terracotta)] mb-4">
            Basic Syntax / Headings
          </p>
          <h1 class="font-serif-display text-[var(--text-inverse)] mb-6">Headings</h1>
          <p class="text-xl text-[var(--text-on-dark)] opacity-80" style="line-height: 1.6;">
            Create different levels of headings using the # symbol. Markdown supports six heading levels.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="container max-w-4xl">
        <div class="prose">
          <h2>Syntax</h2>
          <p>To create a heading, add number signs (#) in front of a word or phrase:</p>

          <pre><code>{`# Heading level 1
## Heading level 2
### Heading level 3
#### Heading level 4
##### Heading level 5
###### Heading level 6`}</code></pre>

          <h2>Preview</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="card my-6">
          <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-medium mb-4">Heading Level 1</h1>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif font-medium mb-4">Heading Level 2</h2>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-medium mb-4">Heading Level 3</h3>
          <h4 class="text-xl font-serif font-medium mb-4">Heading Level 4</h4>
          <h5 class="text-lg font-serif font-medium mb-4">Heading Level 5</h5>
          <h6 class="text-base font-serif font-medium">Heading Level 6</h6>
        </div>

        <div class="prose">
          <h2>Best Practices</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Each page should have only one H1 heading</li>
            <li>Use headings in order — don't skip levels (e.g., don't go from H2 to H4)</li>
            <li>Headings help readers quickly understand the document structure</li>
            <li>Search engines use headings to understand page content</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Alternative Syntax</h2>
          <p>You can also create H1 and H2 headings using underline syntax:</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card my-6">
          <p class="text-lg font-serif mb-2">Heading Level 1 with equals</p>
          <hr class="border-[var(--color-border-warm)] mb-4" />
          <p class="text-base font-serif mb-2">Heading Level 2 with hyphens</p>
          <hr class="border-[var(--color-border-warm)]" />
        </div>

        <div class="prose">
          <pre><code>{`Heading Level 1
===

Heading Level 2
---`}</code></pre>

          <p>While this syntax works in some Markdown processors, we recommend using # syntax as it's more intuitive and widely supported.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <Comments slug="basic-headings" />
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
